You’re not wrong in the abstract.

A program that takes BNF/EBNF and produces an AST is absolutely possible. That is basically what parser generators do:

```ebnf
expr  ::= term (("+" | "-") term)*
term  ::= factor (("*" | "/") factor)*
factor ::= NUMBER | "(" expr ")"
```

From that, a tool can generate a parser that produces something like:

```text
Add(
  Number(1),
  Multiply(Number(2), Number(3))
)
```

So the core idea is sound.

The reason real lexers/parsers get complicated is that **“turn grammar into AST” is only the clean textbook core**. Real languages add a lot of messy requirements.

## 1. Lexing is separated mostly for engineering reasons

A lexer turns raw text into tokens:

```text
let x = 123 + y
```

becomes:

```text
LET IDENT("x") EQUAL NUMBER(123) PLUS IDENT("y")
```

You could avoid a separate lexer and parse characters directly. That is called **scannerless parsing**. It exists.

But separate lexing is useful because many things are easier to handle at the token level:

```text
foo + 123
```

The parser usually does not care whether `foo` is made of `f`, `o`, `o`. It wants `IDENT`.

Similarly, it usually does not care about:

```text
    // comment
```

except that comments and whitespace separate tokens.

So lexing removes low-level noise before parsing.

That said, not every language cleanly separates lexing and parsing. Some languages make lexing context-sensitive.

Example:

```cpp
std::vector<std::vector<int>>
```

In older C++, the `>>` could be tokenized as a right-shift operator, but in templates it may need to mean two closing angle brackets. Context matters.

So even lexing is not always trivial.

## 2. BNF describes syntax, not necessarily the AST you want

A grammar gives you a **parse tree**, not automatically a clean AST.

For example:

```ebnf
expr ::= expr "+" term | term
term ::= term "*" factor | factor
factor ::= NUMBER | "(" expr ")"
```

The parse tree may include lots of syntactic scaffolding:

```text
expr
 ├─ expr
 │   └─ term
 │       └─ factor
 │           └─ NUMBER(1)
 ├─ "+"
 └─ term
     ├─ term
     │   └─ factor
     │       └─ NUMBER(2)
     ├─ "*"
     └─ factor
         └─ NUMBER(3)
```

But the AST you probably want is:

```text
Add(
  Number(1),
  Multiply(Number(2), Number(3))
)
```

Those are not the same thing.

The AST needs decisions like:

```text
Do parentheses become AST nodes?
Do commas become AST nodes?
Do semicolons become AST nodes?
Does `a.b.c` become Field(Field(a, b), c)?
Does `x += 1` become AddAssign(x, 1) or Assign(x, Add(x, 1))?
```

BNF alone usually does not answer those questions.

So a “BNF to AST” tool needs extra annotations or conventions.

## 3. Ambiguity is a huge problem

Many grammars can parse the same input in more than one way.

Classic example:

```text
1 + 2 * 3
```

Could mean:

```text
(1 + 2) * 3
```

or:

```text
1 + (2 * 3)
```

Humans know multiplication binds tighter than addition, but raw grammar needs to encode that.

Another classic example:

```c
if (a)
    if (b)
        x();
    else
        y();
```

Does the `else` belong to the inner `if` or the outer `if`?

Most languages define that it belongs to the nearest unmatched `if`, but the grammar/tool has to handle that.

## 4. Some grammars are easy for humans but hard for machines

You can write a BNF grammar that looks reasonable but is bad for a particular parsing algorithm.

Example:

```ebnf
expr ::= expr "+" term | term
```

This is **left-recursive**. Some parsers handle it fine. Recursive-descent parsers usually do not; they loop forever unless transformed.

So this:

```ebnf
expr ::= expr "+" term | term
```

often becomes:

```ebnf
expr ::= term ("+" term)*
```

Same language, different shape, easier parser.

This is why parser theory has classes like LL, LR, LALR, PEG, GLR, Earley, Pratt, recursive descent, and so on. They are different tradeoffs between grammar flexibility, speed, error messages, ambiguity handling, and implementation simplicity.

## 5. Error handling is harder than successful parsing

Parsing valid code is the easy part.

Real parsers need to handle broken code:

```js
function f(x {
  return x + ;
}
```

A compiler should not just say:

```text
parse failed
```

It should say something useful:

```text
expected ")" after parameter list
expected expression after "+"
```

And an IDE should keep parsing the rest of the file so it can still provide syntax highlighting, autocomplete, outline view, refactoring, diagnostics, and formatting.

This is one of the biggest reasons production parsers are complicated.

A clean “BNF in, AST out” parser often works fine for valid input but gives terrible errors on invalid input.

## 6. Real languages are not purely context-free

BNF/EBNF describes **context-free syntax**.

But real languages often have context-sensitive features.

Example in C:

```c
T * x;
```

Is this multiplication?

```text
T * x
```

or a declaration of pointer `x` of type `T`?

You need to know whether `T` is a type name. That is not purely syntactic; it depends on previous declarations.

Another example:

```rust
foo::<T>(x)
```

Some syntax is only valid depending on language-specific type or name-resolution rules.

So the parser alone may not be able to fully decide the AST without semantic information.

## 7. Performance matters

For a toy language, a general parser can be fine.

For a major compiler or IDE, you may need:

```text
parse millions of lines quickly
recover from errors
support incremental reparsing
preserve comments and whitespace
produce exact source spans
support macros/preprocessors
avoid exponential ambiguity
generate good diagnostics
```

That pushes implementations toward specialized, optimized, sometimes ugly code.

## 8. Some modern tools already do what you are imagining

Your idea exists in several forms:

```text
ANTLR       grammar → lexer/parser/tree
Bison/Yacc  grammar → parser
Menhir      grammar → parser
Tree-sitter grammar → incremental parser
PEG tools   grammar → parser
Nearley     grammar → parser
Ohm         grammar → parse tree/semantics
```

Some are close to “write grammar, get parser.” But the hard parts remain: ambiguity, AST shaping, precedence, error recovery, context-sensitive syntax, and tooling integration.

## The core distinction

A simple parser generator can do this:

```text
valid source code + grammar → parse tree
```

A production language implementation often needs this:

```text
possibly-invalid source code
+ grammar
+ lexical rules
+ precedence rules
+ AST mapping rules
+ error recovery
+ source locations
+ comments/trivia preservation
+ macro/preprocessor handling
+ incremental updates
+ semantic disambiguation
→ useful compiler/IDE data structures
```

That second pipeline is why things feel complex.

## My honest take

You are right that parsing is often made to look more mystical than it is. For many languages, especially small DSLs, you can absolutely build a tool that takes EBNF and emits an AST.

But for a serious general-purpose language, **BNF/EBNF is not enough specification**. It defines the surface grammar, but not all the engineering behavior people expect from a real parser.

A realistic version of your idea would be:

```text
EBNF grammar
+ lexer/token rules, unless scannerless
+ precedence/associativity declarations
+ AST construction annotations
+ error recovery strategy
+ source-span policy
```

Then yes: you can generate a usable parser and AST builder. That is a very reasonable software project.
